[[Image:PotbellyStove.jpg|thumb|Potbelly stove at the [[Museum of Appalachia]]]]
{{Unreferenced|date=January 2017}}
A '''potbelly stove''' is a [[cast iron|cast-iron]] [[wood-burning stove]], round with a bulge in the middle. The name is derived from the resemblance of the stove to that of a fat man's [[Abdominal obesity|pot belly]]. They were designed to heat large spaces and were often found in [[train station]]s or [[One-room school|one-room schoolhouses]]. The flat top of the fireplace allowed for cooking of food, or the heating of water.
==See also== * [[Delamere_Francis_McCloskey#City_Council|Delamere Francis McCloskey]], Los Angeles City Council member, 1941–43, rescued potbelly stoves for use in air-raid defense posts * [[Franklin stove]] * [[List of stoves]] * [[Red Cross stove]]
